args:
The prince looks for a way to stop Phraeganoth,
but a cave-in leaves him and Celliera trapped.
In the darkness, Celliera confides her fears to
the prince, who responds with heartfelt words
of encouragement.
...The heck? We were in the space between\nworlds a second ago.
Perhaps there is a limit to the fragment's\npower.
We couldn't remain there long, and the\nfragment was consumed in the process.
Okay, but that's not a problem, right?
We may have fought him back,\nbut he remains there still.
Phraeganoth will heal, and when he does,\nhe will seek a way to leave his prison.
What, so now we gotta go back in there?!
Even if we wanted to, we have no\notherworld fragment to take us.
Cleo said they come from powerful fiends,\nso we'll just have tâ€”
Yes, I'm fine. But what about the others?
I think it's just the two of us on this side.\nThe falling rocks blocked us in.
So that means we're...buried alive?\n...NO! We have to dig our way out!\nWe have to dig out RIGHT NOW!
Er, maybe we should calm down andâ€”
CALM DOWN?! Once the air in here runs\nout, the two of us are DEAD!
All the more reason to keep still.\nWe'll use it up faster if we panic.
I won't just sit here and wait to die!
My friends are working to save us.
Are you SURE?! What if they left us?!\nWhat if they got scared and ran?!
The idea they took off to save themselves\nhasn't ONCE crossed your mind?!
...I'm sorry. I lost control for a moment.
Oh, believe me, it's understandable.\nBut for now, I think it's best to stay calm\nand wait for help to arrive.
Or, I suppose, I envy the bond you share\nwith your friends.
I'm sure it's much the same with you and\nyour students, Celliera.
My students? No. They despise me.
I know my teaching methods are extreme.
It's not my intention to bully people, but I\nalso can't wait to help them reach their\nfull potential.
To their credit, not one of them ever\ncomplained.
Which likely led me to delude myself into\nthinking I had their trust.
Oh, they made it quite apparent what they\nactually think of me.
When the image of that fiend appeared,\nthey turned and ran. They abandoned me.
I reached out to stop them and they\nslapped my hand away. I called out,\nand not one of them listened.
It wasn't Phraeganoth they were running\nfrom. ...It was me.
And I was so afraid of that fact, I couldn't\nfollow them down the mountain.
I joined you as an excuse to delay the\ntruth, if only for a little while longer.
Heh heh... Aaaah ha ha ha ha ha!\nOh, it's so funny I could cry...
I don't think they hate you, Celliera.
Oh, don't get me wrongâ€”your training is\ninsane. But I also feel your love and\ndedication in every painful rep.
It's obvious you want to make me as strong\nas I can possibly be.
You urged us through it, and praised us\nwhen we were done.
I can't speak for your other students,\nbut I respect the care you've shown me.
So no, I don't believe you scare them as\nmuch as you think you do.
I do. Look, they were in a blind panic when\nthey ran, right?
So put your trust in themâ€”and in the love\nyou've poured into them.
When this fight is over, I'll go face them.
Hey, we got a hole open here!
Are the two of them all right?!
For having gone through such an ordeal,\nyou seem strangely at peace, Celliera.
Perhaps my companion helped me lay a\nfew things to rest.
Nothing to worry about now. Let's turn our\nattention back to Phraeganoth.
We'll need more otherworld fragments,\nso keep watch for any powerful fiends.
